delta_handler: don't apply img->seek to zchunk header memfd

When sw-description specifies `offset = ...` on a delta image entry,
img->seek carries the destination byte offset for the chain handler's
final write. install_delta() correctly memcpys this into the chain
handler's img_type so the assembled image lands at the right place on
the target device.

The bug: install_delta() also calls copyimage(&mem_fd, img, NULL) to
read the zchunk header from the .swu cpio stream into an anonymous
memfd. copyimage's default write callback reads img->seek and lseeks
the destination fd to that offset before writing. mem_fd ends up with
the zchunk header bytes at offset img->seek, and a sparse zero-filled
hole from offset 0 to img->seek-1.

The subsequent `lseek(mem_fd, 0, SEEK_SET); zck_init_read(zckDst, mem_fd)`
then reads zeros instead of the zck magic, and `zck_init_read` fails
with "Invalid lead, perhaps this is not a zck file?"

Reproduces with any A/B partition layout that uses raw byte offsets
on a single block device - i.e. any sw-description shaped like:

    {
        type = "delta";
        device = "/dev/mmcblk0";
        offset = "0xNNNN";
        properties: { url = ...; source = ...; chain = "raw"; };
    }

Fix: clear img->seek across the mem_fd copyimage call. The chain
handler's img already has its own copy of seek from the earlier
memcpy, so it still writes to the right offset.

Upstream-Status: Pending
Signed-off-by: Joey Eamigh <55670930+JoeyEamigh@users.noreply.github.com>

--- a/handlers/delta_handler.c
+++ b/handlers/delta_handler.c
@@ -1003,7 +1003,15 @@ static int install_delta(struct img_type *img,
 		goto cleanup;
 	}

+	/*
+	 * img->seek is the chain handler's destination offset; the mem_fd
+	 * receiving the zchunk header is not a partition and must be
+	 * written from offset 0 so zck_init_read sees the magic at the start.
+	 */
+	unsigned long long save_seek = img->seek;
+	img->seek = 0;
 	ret = copyimage(&mem_fd, img, NULL /* default write callback */);
+	img->seek = save_seek;

 	if (ret != 0) {
 		ERROR("Error %d copying zchunk header, aborting.", ret);
